---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout title="Music by Humans — Tuva Ødegård" lang="en">
  <article>
    <header class="project-header">
      <div class="meta">
        <span class="year">2026</span>
        <span class="badge">Case study</span>
      </div>
      <h1>Music by Humans</h1>
      <p class="lead">An app to filter out AI-generated musicians from your Spotify playlists.</p>
      <ul class="tags">
        <li>UX Design</li>
        <li>User Testing</li>
        <li>Frontend</li>
        <li>Side project</li>
      </ul>
    </header>

    <div class="content">
      <section>
        <h2>Background</h2>
        <p>
          A friend and I noticed that Spotify was filling up with AI-generated
          artists, and there was no way to tell. You could discover a new artist
          you found interesting, start following them, and then find out they
          didn't exist in the real world. Spotify doesn't label AI artists, so
          users have no visible way to distinguish human-made artists from
          algorithmically generated profiles.
        </p>
        <p>
          The issue isn't just aesthetic. It's about trust, and about money.
          Making it as an artist is hard enough already. When someone streams an
          AI track, the royalties go to the bot operator, not a real musician.
          We wanted to make sure real musicians weren't being drowned out by
          content with no human behind it. The goal wasn't necessarily to block
          all AI content, but to create awareness: <em>this is what you're listening to.</em>
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Challenges</h2>
        <p>
          <strong>Blocking isn't possible.</strong> Spotify's API doesn't allow third-party
          apps to remove or block artists directly, and that's something the user
          has to do themselves. This created a fundamental design problem: how do
          you surface information about AI artists without making people feel protected
          when they actually aren't? An app that signals "you're safe" without actually
          doing anything would be worse than nothing.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>The API kept shrinking.</strong> Spotify gradually deprecated useful
          endpoints over the course of the project, which meant features we'd planned
          or built had to be rethought as the platform pulled the rug out from under
          us.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Detection is genuinely hard.</strong> There's no reliable way to
          determine whether an artist is AI-generated, and it kept getting harder.
          We built a scoring system partly as a design response to this, a way to
          be honest that we weren't certain, rather than presenting false confidence.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>First iteration</h2>
        <p>
          I started with rough sketches and lists, mapping out what information
          mattered and how it should be structured. From there I went straight
          into code, implementing the design directly through claude,
          experimenting without detailed designs.
        </p>
        <figure>
          <img
            src={`${base}images/mbh/initial_sketches.jpg`}
            alt="Early sketches mapping out information structure and key screens"
          />
        </figure>
        <p>
          The first version was built around a score, a kind of "AI probability
          index" per artist. The idea was that a percentage and a colour-coded
          bar would let users quickly gauge how likely an artist was to be
          AI-generated.
        </p>
        <figure>
          <img
            src={`${base}images/mbh/old_spotify_frontpage.png`}
            alt="Early landing page design with dark Spotify-inspired theme"
          />
        </figure>
        <figure>
          <img
            src={`${base}images/mbh/old_spotify_tooltip.png`}
            alt="Early logged-in view showing AI probability scores and a tooltip explaining how to block artists"
          />
        </figure>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>User testing</h2>
        <p>
          I put the design in front of some friends in a casual setting. I gave
          them a simple scenario: you saw an Instagram ad that said something
          about listening to AI artists, you tapped it, and now you're here. The
          question was just: "What do you think this is?" It quickly revealed
          where the design was failing.
        </p>
        <p>
          Three things kept coming up. First, the scoring confused people.
          Nobody knew what it meant or which direction was good. Is a high score
          human or AI? Second, nobody understood that blocking was something
          they had to do themselves. The app looked like it was in control, when
          really it was just showing information. Third, the dark
          Spotify-inspired design made people think they were looking at an
          official Spotify feature, which made the confusion worse.
        </p>
        <p>
          That last point led to a deliberate visual reset: the new design uses
          a completely different look to make it immediately clear this is a
          third-party tool, not something built by Spotify.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>The solution</h2>
        <p>
          The redesign moved away from scores entirely. Instead of a number,
          each artist gets a clear label: Human, Possibly AI, or AI Artist. The
          landing page leads with a message for real artists, not a warning
          about robots, setting the right tone before users even log in.
        </p>
        <figure>
          <img
            src={`${base}images/mbh/mbh_frontpage.png`}
            alt="New landing page: Make room for real artists"
          />
        </figure>
        <p>
          After logging in, the dashboard gives an immediate overview of how
          many of your recently played artists might be AI-generated, with a
          prominent "What do I do with this information?" link that explains the
          blocking process step by step. That addressed the biggest
          misunderstanding from testing directly.
        </p>
        <figure>
          <img
            src={`${base}images/mbh/home.png`}
            alt="Dashboard showing playlists and recently played artists with Human and Possibly AI labels"
          />
        </figure>
        <figure>
          <img
            src={`${base}images/mbh/home_what.png`}
            alt="Expanded 'What do I do with this information?' section explaining how to block artists on Spotify"
          />
        </figure>
        <p>
          The artists page splits the list into two clear groups, and each entry
          can be expanded to show more context, including whether the system is
          uncertain.
        </p>
        <figure>
          <img
            src={`${base}images/mbh/artists.png`}
            alt="Artists page split into Possibly AI-generated and Human artists sections"
          />
        </figure>
        <figure>
          <img
            src={`${base}images/mbh/possibly_ai.png`}
            alt="Expanded artist row for 'Neon Drift' showing Possibly AI label, explanation, and Go block artist button"
          />
        </figure>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Reflection</h2>
        <p>
          The project was eventually shelved. Spotify blocked access in a way
          that made it impossible to continue. It's a strange feeling to have a
          platform validate your idea by building their own version of it, which
          Spotify later did. But it also confirmed that the problem was real.
        </p>
        <p>
          The most interesting design challenge wasn't the visual side, it was
          figuring out how to communicate uncertainty. When you can't be certain
          whether an artist is AI-generated, how do you say that without either
          alarming people or being so vague it's useless? That tension shaped
          almost every decision.
        </p>
        <p>
          This was also one of my first projects working closely with Claude
          throughout the process. I wrote very little of the frontend code
          myself. It was a useful way to explore what that kind of collaboration
          looks like in practice, where the thinking and direction is mine, but
          the execution is shared.
        </p>
      </section>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  article {
    max-width: 680px;
  }

  .project-header {
    margin-bottom: 4rem;
    padding-bottom: 2.5rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
  }

  .meta {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .year {
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
  }

  .badge {
    font-size: 0.7rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--accent);
    border: 1px solid var(--accent);
    padding: 0.15rem 0.5rem;
    border-radius: 2px;
  }

  h1 {
    font-size: 2rem;
    font-weight: 400;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.2;
  }

  .lead {
    font-size: 1rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }

  .tags {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.4rem;
    list-style: none;
  }

  .tags li {
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    background: #ede9e2;
    padding: 0.2rem 0.6rem;
    border-radius: 2px;
  }

  .content {
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  .content section {
    margin-bottom: 3rem;
  }

  .content h2 {
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
  }

  .content p {
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .content p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  .content em {
    font-style: italic;
  }

  .content figure {
    margin: 1.5rem 0;
  }

  .content figure img {
    width: 100%;
    border-radius: 4px;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    display: block;
  }
</style>
